arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
Rubble east-west wall south of Locus 25

Locus 29 is an east-west rubble wall just south of Locus 25, abutting the West Precinct Wall. It is an extremely rough wall, made of unhewn sandstone ranging in size from quite small cobbles to boulders. It is one row and one course high, simply stacked together. This locus has been tentatively placed in Stage 4, as it seems to be connected with the reconfiguration of space and use within the complex. It is, however, quite shallow, and could also be much more recent in date.
0.60 m north south -by- 3.92 m east west.
